                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d37">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/10–940: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tuck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-09T13:00:00-03:00"
                            >October 9, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 9—11:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>476. For the Under Secretary. Department’s 236, October 8, 7 p.m.<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d37fn1">Not printed; the Department inquired whether any date had
                        been fixed for staff conversations (810.20 Defense/9–2540).</note> On
                    September 27 Christian and Brereton were asked to meet two Argentine naval
                    captains in order to consider the agenda. On October 4 the conversations opened
                    between our officers and senior officers of the Argentine Army and Navy.
                    Christian and Brereton are satisfied with the interest shown in these informal
                    talks which they consider are progressing slowly but satisfactorily.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tuck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
